        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="Marcellum">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Marcellus, prudens Dux more Romano: sed in bello gerendo magis strenuus, qu&agrave;m prouidus: et ad terrendum hostes, 
                        sa[e]u&egrave; adhuc grassantes, audacior, qu&agrave;m cautior. Potuisset esse virtus, quod euentus probauit vitium. Cauete animosi spiritus: 
                        et circumspect&egrave; ambulate: vt Heroes in nube.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Marcus Claudius Marcellus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Marcellus was a prudent leader in the Roman style, but in warfare more vigorous than prudent, and in frightening the enemy, 
                who were still raging fiercely, more bold than really careful. It could have been valor, which ultimately proved to be a flaw. 
                Watch out bold spirits and tread carefully, like heroes in the fog.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="Marcellum etiam transfixum lancea prolabentem ex equo moribundum uid&ecirc;re">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Egregij Marcelli mors. iactura nimis preciosa Reipub[licae] vsq[ue] ade&ograve; afflicta[e]. Sed Roma, sui similis, cum maxim&egrave; victa, 
                        tum inuicta maxim&egrave;. Etiam Fabio veteratore poste&agrave; defuncto, iuuenis Scipio pra[e]pollet omnibus; et sufficit solus domando Annibali. 
                        Iuuat interim patienter expectare infoelicium medioru[m] foelicem finem. Nec alia h&icirc;c opus consolatione. 
                        Tota ha[e]c Tragoedia, superstitibus Romanis in comoediam euadet.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Marcus Claudius Marcellus"/>
                    <person name="Fabius Maximus"/>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The death of the excellent Marcellus. An unduly precious loss for the Republic troubled to such an extent. 
                But being true to itself, Rome was most invincible when it was most defeated. Even later, after the death of the experienced Fabius, 
                the young Scipio is superior to all, and on his own is capable to subdue Hannibal. Meanwhile it is advantageous patiently to wait for a 
                successful end out of unfortunate intermediate stages. But there is no need here for another consolation. 
                This entire tragedy will turn out as a comedy for the surviving Romans.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="Annibal">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Annibal a craftie Foxe: &amp; euen for theise dayes a notable Example. The finest Politicians, or Pragmaticians may finde in 
                        Liuie to serue theire turne. pregnant practises pro, et contra.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Hannibal"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>vt sa[e]pe s[upr]a, i[nfr]a.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>As often [see] above, below.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
